Thornton Tomasetti L19084.00 Prepared For Bill Linn Capital Project Manager West Virginia University PO Box 6572 979 Rawley Lane Morgantown, WV 26506 Prepared By Thornton Tomasetti, Inc. 1700 Market St, Suite 1750 Philadelphia, PA 19103 +1.267.238.4000 www.ThorntonTomasetti.com December 13, 2019 WVU Milan Puskar South End Zone Screen Upgrades L19084.00 Page i of i Table of Contents 1.0 Introduction and Scope of Work ............................................................................................1 2.0 Design Criteria .........................................................................................................................1 2.1 Gravity Loads.............................................................................................................................2 2.2 Lateral Loads .............................................................................................................................2 3.0 Structural Evaluation and Conclusions .................................................................................2 Appendices Appendix A Structural Reinforcement Sketches Appendix B Documents Reviewed 1.0 Introduction and Scope of Work West Virginia University (WVU) has retained Thornton Tomasetti, Inc. to perform a feasibility study of adding a new scoreboard, graphic signage, and speakers to the existing south end zone scoreboard structure at Milan Puskar Stadium. The existing scoreboard consists of a video board weighing approximately 26,000 pounds with a total surface area exposed to wind of approximately 4,500 square feet. The existing scoreboard is supported by a steel truss spanning approximately 210 feet between cantilevered steel tube columns, which vary from 3-0 to 7-0 in diameter. The columns are approximately 88 feet tall. The existing steel truss typically consists of double-angle diagonals, tube steel verticals, and wide-flange chords. The cantilevered tube steel columns are each supported on a 12 diameter caisson socketed into rock. The proposed upgrades increase the weight supported by the steel structure to approximately 198,000 pounds and increase the surface area exposed to wind to approximately 8,100 square feet. Thornton Tomasetti has conducted a preliminary evaluation of the existing structure. The purpose of this report is to identify the general impact of the proposed changes and provide a basis for preliminary pricing for structural reinforcement. 2.0 Design Criteria This section summarizes the design criteria established for evaluating the existing structure for the loads imposed by the new scoreboard, graphic signage, and speakers, as well as the revised load provisions under the current building code. 2.1 Gravity Loads The approximate weights of the proposed scoreboard, graphic signage and speakers are summarized in Table 1. Table 1: Approximate weights of new scoreboard, signage and speakers Component Quantity Unit Weight (lbs.) Total Weight (lbs.) Scoreboard 1 118,000 118,000 Side Graphic Signage 2 6,000 12,000 Side Speakers 2 4,000 8,000 Top Speaker 1 3,500 3,500 Top Graphic Signage 2 3,600 7,200 The estimated weights are based on the document West Virginia University Mountaineer Field at Milan Puskar Stadium LED Scoreboard Concept 2 provided by WJHW on October 2, 2019, included in Appendix B. Additionally, as part of the scoreboard structure there are four new catwalks proposed along the length of the scoreboard and graphic signage. Overall, the weight of proposed scoreboard, graphic signage, speakers increase the gravity load imposed on the existing structure by a factor of approximately 5. 2.2 Lateral Loads The currently proposed scoreboard and graphic signage additions are governed by the 2015 International Building Code (IBC), which has been adopted by the state of West Virginia. The 2015 IBC references ASCE 7-10, which results in higher design wind pressures than the 2008 scoreboard installation, which was governed by the 2003 IBC. The design of the proposed scoreboard and graphic signage additions fall under the solid freestanding walls and solid signs provisions of ASCE 7-10. Ultimate wind pressures in the governing load case vary from 30.1 to 81.3 pounds per square foot along the length of the scoreboard. This increase in wind pressure, combined with the increase in surface area exposed to wind results in an increase in wind load by a factor of approximately 3.5 as compared to the previous installation governed under IBC 2003. 3.0 Structural Evaluation and Conclusions The results of the structural evaluation of the existing truss structure for the loads imposed by the proposed upgrades are summarized in SK-1 through SK-3 (Appendix A). Approximately 95 members in the existing truss will require some degree of structural reinforcement, totaling approximately 17 tons of reinforcing steel. In addition, approximately 92 existing steel angle connections and approximately 48 steel tube connections require structural reinforcing. Typical conceptual details for member and connection reinforcing are provided in SK-2 and SK-3 (Appendix A). Final tonnages required for structural reinforcement will vary depending on the method and locations of attachment required for the proposed upgrades. In addition to reinforcing of existing steel members and connection, approximately 17 tons of new steel is required to supplement the existing tube columns, consisting of new steel columns with cross-bracing between the new and existing columns. The new columns shall each be supported on a foundation consisting of a reinforced concrete pile cap and micropiles rated to resist 700 kips in tension, 1000 kips in compression, and 150 kips in shear. Foundation loads listed are allowable loads. For estimating purposes, based on previous project experience, at each of the two new columns, assume a 12 long x 9 wide x 5 deep reinforced concrete pile cap with (6) 8 diameter micropiles with a 30 rock socket. A geotechnical engineer will need to be retained to confirm the feasibility of the proposed foundation system, allowable capacities, and other project-specific conditions. Excluded from the tonnages summarized in this report are the following: Steel reinforcing and framing required for access to service the scoreboard, including but not limited to, catwalks, ladders, platforms etc. Supplementary steel framing required to attach the new scoreboard, signage, and speakers to the existing steel structure TTs scope of work for this feasibility study does not include cost estimates, which are to be performed by others. Additionally, TTs scope of work for this feasibility study only included conceptual design. TT understands that the final design will be performed by others who will be the Engineer of Record.
